Notes for ELIAS E. MCVEY:

Monday, Jan. 27, 1947

Elias McVay Dies at Home on Minerva St.

Elias McVay, 81, passed away at his home in Minerva St., this morning after a prolonged illness.

Mr. McVay was employed with the state Highway department, but for the past 12 years he has been retired.

He was born in Washington County on September 1, 1865 the son of Easu and Elizabeth Flint McVay.

He came to Wooster from Washington County in 1923.

Surviving are his wife Mary; the following children; Mrs. Cora E. Clark, of Wooster, Everett W. McVay of Wooster Mrs. Carrie Clark of Wooster, Mrs. Clara Cline of Columbus, Mrs. Nettie Saal of Wooster, Clifford E. McVay of Wooster, and Ms. Amanda Boreman of Wooster; two sisters, Miss Amanda Cline Cline of Reynords Mills, Ohio, and Maranda Kirkpatrick of Butler, Ohio; 23 grandchildren; and 10 great grandchildren.

One daughter, Lucy Stackhouse preceded him in death.

Funeral services will be held from the McIntire Funeral Home on Wednesday afternoon at 1:30 p.m. with the Rev. William McLaln Jr., pastor of the Bethany Baptist Church officiating. Burial will be made in the Wooster Cemetery.

Friends may call at the funeral home Tuesday evening from 7 to 9 o`clock.

 

TWO NAMES OMITTED

Funeral services of Elias McVay, who died yesterday at his home on Minerva Street will be held Wednesday at 1:30 at the McIntire Funeral Home.

In yesterday's account of the death, names of two daughters were omitted from the list of survivors. They are Mrs. Opal Pearl Garst of Wooster, Mrs. Velma Miller of Shreve.

 

Wednesday, Jan. 29, 1947

Funeral Services for Elias McVay who passed away at his home on Minerva st., on Monday, were held frpm McIntire Funeral Home this afternoon. The Rev. William McClaln Jr., pastor of the Bethany Baptist Church officiated at the services.

Pallbearers were the following: Wallace Saal, Jess Garst, Wiley Cline, Emerson Boreman, George Miller, John Kostenbader.

Burial was made in the Wooster Cemetery.

 

 

Elias McVay, was born Sept. 1, 1865. The son of Mr. Easu and Elizabeth Flint McVay of Washington County, Ohio.

He was united in marriage to Mary Louise Burris on March 11, 1894 by the Rev. T. S. Barnes.

The Lord richly blessed their union with ten children. whose names are follows:

Mrs. Cora E. Clark, of Wooster, Everett McVay of Wooster Lucy Stackhouse now deceased Mrs. Nettie Saal of Wooster, Mr. Clifford McVay of Wooster, Mrs. Velma Miller of Shreve, Mrs. Opal Garst of Wooster, Ms. Amanda Boreman of Wooster.

He also had twenty-three grandchildren living and three deceased. He also had ten great grandchildren.

Notes for MARY LOUISE BURRIS:

December 28, 1961

Mary McVey, Widow of Elias

Mrs. Mary Louise Burris McVey, 86, widow of Elias McVey, died early this morning at her home 212 Minerva St., Wooster, following a long illness.

She was born in Washington County and lived on a farm there until moving to Wooster 37 years ago.

Surviving are seven daughters, Mrs. S. M. (Cora) Clark, of Garland, Texas, Mrs. Frank (Carrie) Clark of Wooster, Mrs. Wiley (Clara) Cline of New Matamoras: Mrs. Wallace (Nettie) Saal of Wooster,

Mrs. S. (Velma) Branan of Gladewater, Texas Mrs. J. E. (Opal) Garaft of Wooster RD 1; and Mrs. Amanda Boreman of Wooster.

Also two sons Everett W. McVey and Clifford E. McVey both of Wooster, 24 grandchildren; 37 great grandchildren; and a great - great grandchild.

Her husband Elias McVey a daughter, Mrs. Lewis (Lucy) Stackhouse of Rittman; and four grandchildren died previously.

Private service will be held at the Pim Funeral Home Saturday at 1:30 p.m. Burial will be in Wooster Cemetry.

Friends may call at the funeral home Friday from 7 - 9 p.m.

 

December 30, 1961

Burris Services Held

Funeral Services for Mrs. Mary Louise Burris McVey, widow of Elias, who died at her home at Minerva Street in Wooster, Dec 28, were held Saturday afternoon at Pim Funeral Home.

Rev. Leo A. Kell conducted the serviers.

Pallbearers were Wiley Cline, Jesse E. and Ronald E. Garst, Wallace Saal, John Kostenbader, and Raymond Yeagley.

Burial was in Wooster Cemetery.

 

Card of Thanks

We wish to thank everyone who helped and assisted us in any way during the losing illness and death of our mother ---- Mrs Mary McVey. We especially want to thank Rev. Leo Kell, Dr. Robertson and the Pim Funeral Home for their services.

The Children and their families.

Notes for EVERETT W. MCVEY:

Everett W. McVey, 73, of Wooster RD 4, died Tuesday afternoon at Orrville Osteopathic Hospital following a long illness.

He was born Jan. 6, 1897, in Washington County to Elias and Mary Burris McVey.

He had lived in Wooster for 52 years.

He had been a rig builder in the oil fields and later was a partner in the McVey and Young Filling Station on West Liberty St. Later he was elevator operator at the Peoples Federal Buildling.

He served in the Army during World War I.

He is survived by his wife, Amy C. McVey; a son, W. Carl McVey, and a daughter, Mrs. John (Grace) Yeagley, both of Wooster; seven grandchildren; two great-grandchildren; seven sisters, Mrs. Cora Clark of Garland, Tex., Mrs. Clara Cline and Mrs. Carrie Clark, both of New Metamoras, Mrs. Nettie Saal, Mrs. Opal Garst, and Mrs. Amanda Boreman, all of Wooster, Mrs. Velma Brannan of Gladewater, Tex.; and a brother, Clifford E. McVey, of Wooster, His parents, and one sister, Mrs. Lucy Stackhouse, died previously.

Services will be Friday at 2 p.m. at the Pim Funeral Home with Rev. Paul Tewell officiating. Burial will be in Overton. Friends may call at the funeral home Thursday 7 - 9 p.m.

 

Everett McVey

Services for Everett McVey, who died Tuesday, were held Friday.

Pallbears were Howard Yeagley; Harry Young, Carl Snoddy, George Topovski, Loren Sigler and John Kostenbader.

Members of American Legion Post 68 conferred military honors at the cemetery, with Jane Yost acting as bugler. The flag present was made by members of Barricks 1600. Burial was in Overton.

THURSDAY JUNE 30, 2005

 

Nettie Saal

 

LEXINGTON - Nettie M. Saal, 101, went home to be with her Lord on Monday morning, June 27, 2005, at her home. She was formerly of Wooster.

 

Services will be Friday at 1 p.m. at Custer-Glenn Funeral Home, 2284 Benden Drive, Wooster, with Pastor Ermon French officiating. Private family interment will be at Wooster Cemetery.

 

Friends may call one hour prior to the services. Words of comfort may be shared with the family at www.MEM.com.

 

In lieu of flowers, contributions may be made to First Baptist Church, 246 N. Market St., Wooster 44691.

 

She was born Nov. 15, 1903, in Washington County to Elias and Mary L. (Burris) McVay and married Wallace R. Saal on April 8, 1925, in Wooster. He went home to be with his Lord in November 1990.

 

She moved to Wooster in 1920, and was a devoted homemaker.

 

Nettie was a member of First Baptist Church in Wooster and was a Cleveland Indians fan, an avid reader and enjoyed crocheting.

 

Surviving are a daughter, Evelyn Saal-Montanya of Lexington; five grandchildren; six great-grandchildren; two step-great-grandchildren; two great-great-grandchildren; and many nieces and nephews.

 

In addition to her loving husband, her parents, seven sisters and two brothers died previously.

Memorial Clifford McVey

Clifford Earl McVey, 74, of 4656 Old Lincoln Way West, Friday afternoon at Smithville-Western Care Center following a seven month illness.

Services will be Monday at 2 p.m. at Murray Funeral Home in Wooster with the Revs. Harrison R. Aspinal and George Myers officiating. Burial will be at Reedsburg Cemetery. Friends may call Sunday from 7-9 p.m. at the funeral Home.
